.SH "NAME"
git-mktag \- Creates a tag object
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
.nf
\fIgit mktag\fR < signature_file
.fi
.sp
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
Readz a tag contents on standard input n' creates a tag object dat can also be used ta sign other objects\&.
.sp
Da output is tha freshly smoked up tag\(cqs <object> identifier\&.
.SH "TAG FORMAT"
.sp
A tag signature file has a straight-up simple fixed format: four lines of
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
object <sha1>
type <typename>
tag <tagname>
tagger <tagger>
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp
followed by some \fIoptional\fR free\-form message (some tags pimped by olda Git may not have tagger line)\&. Da message, when exists, is separated by a funky-ass blank line from tha header\&. Da message part may contain a signature dat Git itself don\(cqt care bout yo, but dat can be verified wit gpg\&.
